definition: old, well-known brand/old style/old school/an old hand/experienced veteran

prefix used before the surname of a person or a numeral indicating the order of birth of the children in a family or to indicate affection or familiarity/old (of people)/venerable (person)/experienced/of long standing/always/all the time/of the past/very/outdated/(of meat etc) tough

sentences.english: When we exam the brand, you will see Mercedes-Benz actually is a contributor to auto safety.

The veteran crooner took out his anger over a leaked record on a producer.

sentences.english: Hong Kong Broadband’s principal competitor is an older company, PCCW, which has several other lines of business, including phone, television and mobile.

sentences.english: One of my favourite places to eat it is in the traditional comfort of Wilton’s.

sentences.english: The two leaders in old-fashioned videoconferencing, Polycom and Tandberg, are switching to telepresence.

sentences.english: But Gibson says the brain drain from old-guard companies may not last.
sentences.chinese: 但吉布森称老牌公司的人才流失不会持续很久。

sentences.english: The incumbent and the rising powers compete for dominance.
sentences.chinese: 老牌大国和新兴大国竞逐主导地位。

definition: an up-and-coming youngster/new talent/a brilliant younger generation
peak/apex/world best/number one/finest (competitors)/top (figures in a certain field)
a powerful chief of the princes of the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 BC)/overlord/hegemon
tycoon/magnate/big player (including company, country, school etc)/big shot
to rise abruptly (to a towering position)/to tower over/to spring up/to emerge suddenly/the emergence (e.g. of a power)
lit. late-comer lives above (idiom); the up-and-coming youngster outstrips the older generation/the pupil surpasses the master
to count as number one (idiom); second to none/outstanding
